ce:section.ce:para:
After a simple microwave treatment with BCDs/ BPCDs and urea-mixed aqueous solution, the BCD/ BPCD composites were synthesized (Schematic of the fabrication process was shown in Scheme 1
                        ). The processes of CDs incorporated into the matrix effectively prevent aggregation, which realizes the solid-state luminescence, and these composites also present excellent afterglow emission properties. The photophysical properties of BCD/ BPCD composites were investigated in detail, and the absorption spectra of these composite powders were compared with CD aqueous solution first. As shown in Fig. 2
                        a, BPCDs and their composite exhibit broader absorption bands in 300–500 nm than BCDs, which could further verify the dropping of the P elements change the bandgap. At room temperature, the BCD and BPCD composite powders could exhibit bright blue and cyan luminescent emission under the 365 nm UV light, and after turning off the UV light, a blue and cyan afterglow emission also could be observed for 10 s and 15 s by the naked eye at least (as shown in Fig. 2g). The photoluminescence excitation-emission maps of BCD/ BPCD composites were measured and shown in Fig. 2b and c, respectively. For the BCD composite powders, blue emission centers at 410 nm with PLQY of 39 % could be observed in 3D spectra, and the BPCD composite powders exhibit emission peaks at around 425 nm and 508 nm with PLQY of 44.6 % (under 360 nm excited). After the carbonization process, the fluorescence emission center between CDs aqueous solution and composite powders have a noticeable change.
